1
00:00:04,720 --> 00:00:07,480
At some point, keeping my streak alive

2
00:00:07,480 --> 00:00:09,960
mattered more than actually learning.

3
00:00:09,960 --> 00:00:11,760
Why does breaking a streak feel so

4
00:00:11,760 --> 00:00:13,920
terrible? And are streaks actually

5
00:00:13,920 --> 00:00:16,640
helping us build habits or just making

6
00:00:16,640 --> 00:00:18,720
us afraid to stop?

7
00:00:18,720 --> 00:00:22,120
Here's what I found after looking at 859

8
00:00:22,120 --> 00:00:24,440
streak designs on Mobbin. Every streak

9
00:00:24,440 --> 00:00:26,720
design revolves around this question.

10
00:00:26,720 --> 00:00:29,440
What makes us come back tomorrow? Let's

11
00:00:29,440 --> 00:00:31,320
start with the most obvious pattern,

12
00:00:31,320 --> 00:00:34,360
fear. Let's say you won $10 today. It

13
00:00:34,360 --> 00:00:37,480
feels nice. Now, imagine losing $10

14
00:00:37,480 --> 00:00:40,080
instead. It stings way more.

15
00:00:40,080 --> 00:00:42,320
This is what we call loss aversion.

16
00:00:42,320 --> 00:00:45,240
Streak mechanics bet on this.

17
00:00:45,240 --> 00:00:48,800
The copy becomes more urgent.

18
00:00:48,800 --> 00:00:51,000
The clock starts counting down.

19
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:53,200
And look, an angry owl giving you a

20
00:00:53,200 --> 00:00:55,680
sense of guilt. Fear-based streaks work

21
00:00:55,680 --> 00:00:57,240
because we're protecting something we

22
00:00:57,240 --> 00:00:58,960
could lose.

23
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:00,960
Now, some streak systems lean on

24
00:01:00,960 --> 00:01:03,240
optimism. These designs make us feel

25
00:01:03,240 --> 00:01:05,000
like we're building towards a better

26
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,160
version of ourselves.

27
00:01:07,160 --> 00:01:10,240
Copy is positive and encouraging.

28
00:01:10,240 --> 00:01:12,960
Even tiny shifts to calls to actions.

29
00:01:12,960 --> 00:01:15,080
Duolingo's product team tested these

30
00:01:15,080 --> 00:01:17,120
copy changes. We used to say continue

31
00:01:17,120 --> 00:01:19,320
and we changed that to commit to my goal

32
00:01:19,320 --> 00:01:21,440
and it was like a massive win.

33
00:01:21,440 --> 00:01:23,960
More and more apps are doing this today.

34
00:01:23,960 --> 00:01:25,840
Reframing a call to action into a

35
00:01:25,840 --> 00:01:29,200
promise you make to yourself.

36
00:01:29,200 --> 00:01:31,320
Some apps even turn streaks into

37
00:01:31,320 --> 00:01:35,120
collectibles, like badges, milestones,

38
00:01:35,120 --> 00:01:38,240
and tangible proof of progress.

39
00:01:38,240 --> 00:01:41,040
In Opal, your streak earns you literal

40
00:01:41,040 --> 00:01:43,040
milestones that you can collect over

41
00:01:43,040 --> 00:01:44,840
time.

42
00:01:44,840 --> 00:01:46,680
I noticed I wasn't opening Duolingo

43
00:01:46,680 --> 00:01:48,560
because I cared about the streak number

44
00:01:48,560 --> 00:01:51,160
anymore. I opened because I didn't want

45
00:01:51,160 --> 00:01:54,000
to disappoint Duo. It's just a cartoon

46
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:56,840
owl, just pixels, but I still felt it.

47
00:01:56,840 --> 00:01:58,680
So, I looked into why.

48
00:01:58,680 --> 00:02:01,040
When we assign human emotions to

49
00:02:01,040 --> 00:02:03,080
non-human things, it's called

50
00:02:03,080 --> 00:02:05,240
anthropomorphism.

51
00:02:05,240 --> 00:02:07,400
That's why we yell at computers, name

52
00:02:07,400 --> 00:02:11,120
our cars, and apologize [music] to AI.

53
00:02:11,120 --> 00:02:13,200
Software uses this, too.

54
00:02:13,200 --> 00:02:14,800
A mascot cheering you on like it

55
00:02:14,800 --> 00:02:17,080
believes in you.

56
00:02:17,080 --> 00:02:20,120
A little bird growing alongside you.

57
00:02:20,120 --> 00:02:22,560
So, back in the '90s, people got

58
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:25,080
emotionally attached to these tiny

59
00:02:25,080 --> 00:02:26,880
virtual pets you had to feed [music] and

60
00:02:26,880 --> 00:02:29,200
care for. Tamagotchi, the original

61
00:02:29,200 --> 00:02:31,160
virtual reality pet. Your care

62
00:02:31,160 --> 00:02:33,520
determines the pets you get from Bandai.

63
00:02:33,520 --> 00:02:35,400
If you ignored your Tamagotchi, they

64
00:02:35,400 --> 00:02:36,959
would literally die.

65
00:02:36,959 --> 00:02:39,160
People carried them everywhere, even

66
00:02:39,160 --> 00:02:42,120
grieved when they died. This is called

67
00:02:42,120 --> 00:02:43,959
the Tamagotchi effect. It's the

68
00:02:43,959 --> 00:02:46,280
attachment that forms when a digital

69
00:02:46,280 --> 00:02:49,600
thing appears to need you back.

70
00:02:49,600 --> 00:02:53,880
Duolingo took it further than most.

71
00:02:57,400 --> 00:03:00,080
It became a personality. I realized that

72
00:03:00,080 --> 00:03:02,120
mascots aren't just there to make apps

73
00:03:02,120 --> 00:03:04,720
feel cute. They're designed to create

74
00:03:04,720 --> 00:03:06,280
attachment.

75
00:03:06,280 --> 00:03:07,800
The moment you feel something for a

76
00:03:07,800 --> 00:03:10,640
product, the barrier to leaving feels a

77
00:03:10,640 --> 00:03:13,120
lot higher. And maybe that's why we care

78
00:03:13,120 --> 00:03:17,000
so much about a cartoon owl.

79
00:03:18,239 --> 00:03:21,400
Some streak systems don't rely on fear,

80
00:03:21,400 --> 00:03:24,360
hope, or attachment. They work through

81
00:03:24,360 --> 00:03:26,120
visual attention.

82
00:03:26,120 --> 00:03:28,760
They all turn consistency into a visible

83
00:03:28,760 --> 00:03:31,760
pattern. Once there's a gap, our brain

84
00:03:31,760 --> 00:03:33,840
notices it immediately.

85
00:03:33,840 --> 00:03:36,600
Part of this relates to the Zeigarnik

86
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:39,519
effect. Unfinished things stay active in

87
00:03:39,519 --> 00:03:42,320
our mind longer than completed ones.

88
00:03:42,320 --> 00:03:44,480
That's why filling one tiny missing

89
00:03:44,480 --> 00:03:46,800
block feels strangely satisfying, and

90
00:03:46,800 --> 00:03:49,200
why breaking the chain feels worse than

91
00:03:49,200 --> 00:03:50,720
it probably should.

92
00:03:50,720 --> 00:03:53,000
These mechanics are everywhere, even in

93
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:54,640
places that have nothing to do with

94
00:03:54,640 --> 00:03:57,040
self-improvement. Different interfaces

95
00:03:57,040 --> 00:03:59,077
with the same underlying idea, giving

96
00:03:59,077 --> 00:04:01,000
[music] people something they don't want

97
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,320
to break. These patterns keep pulling us

98
00:04:03,320 --> 00:04:06,760
back, but why? What's actually working

99
00:04:06,760 --> 00:04:07,720
here?

100
00:04:07,720 --> 00:04:09,800
We tend to think dopamine is the

101
00:04:09,800 --> 00:04:12,480
chemical our brain releases after

102
00:04:12,480 --> 00:04:14,680
something rewarding happens, but

103
00:04:14,680 --> 00:04:16,760
Professor Schultz found that dopamine

104
00:04:16,760 --> 00:04:19,280
doesn't just respond to rewards. It

105
00:04:19,280 --> 00:04:22,002
responds to the prediction of rewards.

106
00:04:22,002 --> 00:04:23,040
[music]

107
00:04:23,040 --> 00:04:24,919
The smell of coffee before our first

108
00:04:24,919 --> 00:04:27,600
sip, the notification chime before we

109
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:29,720
even read it. Our brain starts to

110
00:04:29,720 --> 00:04:31,919
reacting to [music] what it thinks is

111
00:04:31,919 --> 00:04:34,600
coming next, which means a streak

112
00:04:34,600 --> 00:04:36,400
doesn't need to feel satisfying every

113
00:04:36,400 --> 00:04:39,240
single time. It just needs to make our

114
00:04:39,240 --> 00:04:42,160
brain feel like something satisfying is

115
00:04:42,160 --> 00:04:45,360
about to happen. And that's exactly what

116
00:04:45,360 --> 00:04:48,080
the habit loop is built around. Almost

117
00:04:48,080 --> 00:04:50,040
every habit follows the same four

118
00:04:50,040 --> 00:04:52,960
stages. The first stage, cue, something

119
00:04:52,960 --> 00:04:55,400
that triggers the anticipation before we

120
00:04:55,400 --> 00:04:59,160
even open the app. Then comes craving.

121
00:04:59,160 --> 00:05:01,200
The Duolingo jingle after each lesson

122
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:02,919
makes us want the next one.

123
00:05:02,919 --> 00:05:05,720
Next, response. Make it easy so we'll do

124
00:05:05,720 --> 00:05:07,880
it, like auto progressing to the next

125
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:10,000
step. Finally, the reward. [music]

126
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:12,160
It's that satisfying feeling our brain

127
00:05:12,160 --> 00:05:14,360
spent the last minute anticipating.

128
00:05:14,360 --> 00:05:16,160
Studies found that when people are

129
00:05:16,160 --> 00:05:18,440
reminded of their streak, just seeing

130
00:05:18,440 --> 00:05:20,560
the number, they're more likely to keep

131
00:05:20,560 --> 00:05:22,760
going. We haven't even opened the app

132
00:05:22,760 --> 00:05:24,840
yet, but the cue already triggered the

133
00:05:24,840 --> 00:05:26,919
loop. That's what makes us want to come

134
00:05:26,919 --> 00:05:29,919
back tomorrow, not the lesson, not even

135
00:05:29,919 --> 00:05:33,440
the streak, but the habit loop itself.

136
00:05:33,440 --> 00:05:36,080
But if just seeing the streak is enough

137
00:05:36,080 --> 00:05:38,520
to pull us back in, why do people give

138
00:05:38,520 --> 00:05:41,640
up entirely after breaking a streak? The

139
00:05:41,640 --> 00:05:44,280
longer the streak, the more our identity

140
00:05:44,280 --> 00:05:46,560
gets wrapped up in it.

141
00:05:46,560 --> 00:05:48,680
The obvious solution to this would be

142
00:05:48,680 --> 00:05:50,840
making your streaks stricter, adding

143
00:05:50,840 --> 00:05:53,320
more pressure and accountability, but

144
00:05:53,320 --> 00:05:55,520
Duolingo found the opposite worked

145
00:05:55,520 --> 00:05:57,360
better. They implemented a feature

146
00:05:57,360 --> 00:05:59,840
called streak freeze that lets you miss

147
00:05:59,840 --> 00:06:02,480
a day without losing everything. And

148
00:06:02,480 --> 00:06:04,440
when Duolingo allowed users to equip up

149
00:06:04,440 --> 00:06:07,200
to two streak freezes at a time, daily

150
00:06:07,200 --> 00:06:10,520
active learners increased by 0.38%.

151
00:06:10,520 --> 00:06:12,680
That's over 200,000 more people coming

152
00:06:12,680 --> 00:06:14,880
back every day. People were more likely

153
00:06:14,880 --> 00:06:17,360
to keep going after failure when goals

154
00:06:17,360 --> 00:06:20,200
included a little built-in flexibility.

155
00:06:20,200 --> 00:06:22,840
Duolingo tested two variants. First,

156
00:06:22,840 --> 00:06:25,360
users must hit their full daily goal in

157
00:06:25,360 --> 00:06:27,600
order to preserve the streak.

158
00:06:27,600 --> 00:06:29,400
The second variant is where users could

159
00:06:29,400 --> 00:06:31,240
keep their streak alive by just

160
00:06:31,240 --> 00:06:33,840
completing one lesson on Duolingo.

161
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:35,840
This variant won.

162
00:06:35,840 --> 00:06:38,640
Over 40% more people maintained their

163
00:06:38,640 --> 00:06:41,000
7-day streak. More and more apps are

164
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:42,680
designing streaks around recovery

165
00:06:42,680 --> 00:06:45,680
instead of perfection. Repairs, freezing

166
00:06:45,680 --> 00:06:48,720
your streaks, pauses, and giving people

167
00:06:48,720 --> 00:06:51,200
grace days. But that raises a bigger

168
00:06:51,200 --> 00:06:53,880
question. Do streaks actually help

169
00:06:53,880 --> 00:06:56,400
people build long-term habits or are

170
00:06:56,400 --> 00:06:58,200
they just really good at making people

171
00:06:58,200 --> 00:06:59,560
come back? [music]

172
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:01,600
On hindsight, streaks seem like the

173
00:07:01,600 --> 00:07:03,760
perfect habit-building system. All we

174
00:07:03,760 --> 00:07:05,840
need to do is to show up every day and

175
00:07:05,840 --> 00:07:07,760
eventually the behavior became

176
00:07:07,760 --> 00:07:10,520
automatic. But the more I research, the

177
00:07:10,520 --> 00:07:12,680
more I notice that most evidence around

178
00:07:12,680 --> 00:07:14,680
streaks focuses on engagement and

179
00:07:14,680 --> 00:07:17,080
retention, not necessarily lasting

180
00:07:17,080 --> 00:07:19,000
behavioral change.

181
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:21,520
We know that dopamine responds to the

182
00:07:21,520 --> 00:07:23,680
prediction or the anticipation of

183
00:07:23,680 --> 00:07:26,200
reward. But once the streak becomes

184
00:07:26,200 --> 00:07:29,040
routine, when things become predictable,

185
00:07:29,040 --> 00:07:31,520
that dopamine signal actually weakens.

186
00:07:31,520 --> 00:07:35,000
So, apps keep layering in new surprises.

187
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:36,640
Animations,

188
00:07:36,640 --> 00:07:39,000
milestone celebrations,

189
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:40,800
bonus XP.

190
00:07:40,800 --> 00:07:42,160
They're all manufacturing

191
00:07:42,160 --> 00:07:46,880
unpredictability to keep the loop alive.

192
00:07:48,400 --> 00:07:51,200
But, optimizing for engagement and

193
00:07:51,200 --> 00:07:54,240
optimizing for long-term habit formation

194
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:57,160
is not the same thing. So, what actually

195
00:07:57,160 --> 00:07:59,760
makes habits stick?

196
00:07:59,760 --> 00:08:01,800
Most streak systems are designed around

197
00:08:01,800 --> 00:08:03,320
never missing a day, right? We got to

198
00:08:03,320 --> 00:08:05,680
show up every single day to keep our

199
00:08:05,680 --> 00:08:07,160
streak moving.

200
00:08:07,160 --> 00:08:09,320
A study tracked people building real

201
00:08:09,320 --> 00:08:11,520
habits over months and found that

202
00:08:11,520 --> 00:08:14,640
missing a day had almost no effect on

203
00:08:14,640 --> 00:08:17,480
whether the behavior eventually became

204
00:08:17,480 --> 00:08:20,425
automatic. People simply resumed and the

205
00:08:20,425 --> 00:08:22,760
[music] habit continued, which is the

206
00:08:22,760 --> 00:08:25,840
opposite of how most streak systems are

207
00:08:25,840 --> 00:08:27,600
designed.

208
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:30,560
Maybe what matters isn't how long you

209
00:08:30,560 --> 00:08:33,200
keep your streak. It's whether you come

210
00:08:33,200 --> 00:08:36,145
back even after breaking it. And that's

211
00:08:36,145 --> 00:08:38,080
[music] good news to me. Now I know that

212
00:08:38,080 --> 00:08:42,280
one bad day doesn't erase everything.

213
